query: Which episode was the most unpopular in Skins, and why?
summary: The most unpopular episode of Skins was Episode 5, titled "Stanley". The episode had the lowest viewership of the series, with only 0.96 million US viewers tuning in. This was likely due to the episode focusing on Stanley Lucerne. Additionally, the episode was written by Jamie Brittain and Mark Hammer, who had not been involved in writing any of the preceding episodes. This lack of familiarity and connection with the series may have caused the episode to be the least popular.

query: How has the title of the "Tallest building in Fort Wayne" transitioned over time among the buildings listed with the respective years?
summary: The title of the "Tallest building in Fort Wayne" has transitioned over time among various buildings as the city's skyline evolved. Initially, the Lincoln Bank Tower held the title from 1930 to 1970, as it was not only the tallest in Fort Wayne but also in Indiana. However, in 1970, the PNC Center surpassed its height and became the tallest in Fort Wayne until 1982, when the Indiana Michigan Power Center was completed and took the title, which it still holds today.

query: What was the trend in Kevin Cogan's start and finish positions from 1981 to 1993 in the Indianapolis 500, and how did changes in his chassis, engine, and entrant influence this trend?
summary: T93 chassis, racing for Raulerson Racing. Throughout Kevin Cogan's career at the Indianapolis 500, there are a few key takeaways. Performance-wise, his best years were undoubtedly in 1981, 1983, and 1986. Although he did not win the race during any of these years, he achieved 4th, 5th, and 2nd place finishes respectively. 1986 was particularly exceptional for him, achieving his only front-row start in his Indy 500 career, and narrowly missing out on victory. Furthermore, one can see how crucial the combination of the chassis and engine was for Cogan's overall performance.
